definition: "Alkaline phosphatase (ALP) is a hydrolase enzyme that removes phosphate groups from various molecules at alkaline pH. It is expressed in multiple tissues throughout the body — most importantly the liver (bile canalicular membranes), bone (osteoblasts), kidneys, small intestine, and placenta — each producing distinct isoenzymes that can be differentiated with specialized testing. The ALP measured in a standard blood test reflects the aggregate of all tissue sources, with liver and bone typically contributing the majority in adults. In clinical medicine, ALP elevation is most commonly used to screen for liver disease (particularly cholestatic or obstructive patterns affecting bile flow) and bone disease (increased osteoblast activity in Paget's disease, bone metastases, hyperparathyroidism, or growing bone). Serum ALP reflects the activity of the enzyme being released from these tissues into the bloodstream — elevated levels indicate increased enzyme production or release from its tissue sources."
why_it_matters: "ALP is a standard component of every comprehensive metabolic panel (CMP) and liver function test, yet it is paradoxically one of the least explained markers in routine clinical communication. Most patients are told only whether their ALP is 'normal' or 'elevated,' without understanding what the number reflects or how to contextualize it. In longevity medicine, ALP matters for two somewhat opposite reasons: elevated ALP signals pathology in the liver or bone that warrants investigation; but increasingly, very low ALP is recognized as a marker associated with metabolic dysfunction and all-cause mortality in population studies. The normal ALP range is wide, and where someone sits within it carries information — particularly when interpreted alongside GGT (which, when elevated alongside ALP, confirms the liver as the source), ALT and AST (which, when co-elevated, suggest hepatocellular rather than cholestatic liver injury), and the clinical history."

